1
00:00:09,583 --> 00:00:11,416
[NARRATOR]
Beasts known as the Nemesis

2
00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:13,375
wreak havoc on mankind.

3
00:00:13,458 --> 00:00:16,000
The only humans who can
stand against them

4
00:00:16,083 --> 00:00:17,958
are those called sorcerers.

5
00:00:18,041 --> 00:00:21,500
However, sorcerers are seen
as tainted by most,

6
00:00:21,583 --> 00:00:25,958
and are regarded
with fear and distrust.

7
00:00:26,041 --> 00:00:29,041
♪

8
00:00:32,541 --> 00:00:34,000
[ground cracking]

9
00:00:34,083 --> 00:00:35,291
[grunting]

10
00:00:35,375 --> 00:00:36,375
[yelling]

11
00:00:37,666 --> 00:00:39,291
[exploding]

12
00:00:40,375 --> 00:00:41,958
[yelling]

13
00:00:43,958 --> 00:00:45,541
[SETH gasps]

14
00:00:51,750 --> 00:00:54,791
[SETH whimpering]

15
00:00:58,416 --> 00:00:59,875
[MELIE groans]

16
00:00:59,958 --> 00:01:01,291
[MELIE]
You monster.

17
00:01:01,375 --> 00:01:02,875
[SETH panting]

18
00:01:02,958 --> 00:01:04,750
[panicked gasping]

19
00:01:04,833 --> 00:01:06,750
[panting]

20
00:01:06,833 --> 00:01:09,291
[SETH] You're okay, Seth.
It was only a dream.

21
00:01:09,375 --> 00:01:11,833
It was nothing.
Just a nightmare.

22
00:01:11,916 --> 00:01:14,333
[wind rushing]

23
00:01:14,416 --> 00:01:16,375
[paper rustling]

24
00:01:18,875 --> 00:01:20,166
[sighs]

25
00:02:55,041 --> 00:02:56,750
[NARRATOR]
"Omen."

26
00:03:00,416 --> 00:03:02,500
[LISELOTTE] More information
keeps coming to light

27
00:03:02,583 --> 00:03:04,208
about Konrad's actions.

28
00:03:04,291 --> 00:03:07,250
The idiot used his position
as an Inquisitor Captain

29
00:03:07,333 --> 00:03:10,208
to try and wipe out all
of Rumble Town's immigrants.

30
00:03:10,291 --> 00:03:13,708
And to do it, he even colluded
with a domitor.

31
00:03:13,791 --> 00:03:15,041
Goodness me.

32
00:03:15,125 --> 00:03:17,000
What a shameful way
to behave.

33
00:03:17,083 --> 00:03:20,916
Ha. He didn't realize
that he was the one being used.

34
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,791
His crimes from fifteen years
back were exposed.

35
00:03:23,875 --> 00:03:26,000
The one-time Champion
of Rumble Town

36
00:03:26,083 --> 00:03:28,791
is now known by all
as a villain.

37
00:03:28,875 --> 00:03:31,125
Which would be fine,
except it's damaged

38
00:03:31,208 --> 00:03:33,166
the public's trust
in the Inquisition.

39
00:03:33,250 --> 00:03:34,625
[TORQUE sighs]

40
00:03:34,708 --> 00:03:37,000
That brainless muscle-head.

41
00:03:37,083 --> 00:03:39,541
He weakened us more than
any sorcerer could.

42
00:03:39,625 --> 00:03:40,708
[SANTORI]
Fear not.

43
00:03:40,791 --> 00:03:43,208
Public opinion
is easily swayed.

44
00:03:43,291 --> 00:03:47,083
We need only stay our course
to regain their trust over time.

45
00:03:47,166 --> 00:03:50,000
How can you be
so dismissive of this?

46
00:03:50,083 --> 00:03:52,333
And what are your thoughts,
General Torque?

47
00:03:55,125 --> 00:03:58,750
What matters right now is the
upcoming campaign in Cyfandir.

48
00:03:58,833 --> 00:04:01,041
Ha! Yes. Good.

49
00:04:01,125 --> 00:04:03,750
Oh. Are we finally
going to do something

50
00:04:03,833 --> 00:04:06,250
about those repulsive
sorcerer knights?

51
00:04:06,333 --> 00:04:09,875
We aren't the only foreigners
with eyes on Cyfandir,

52
00:04:09,958 --> 00:04:12,166
and those Caislean knights
are quite strong.

53
00:04:12,250 --> 00:04:14,125
Is this really a war
that we want?

54
00:04:14,208 --> 00:04:15,708
Of course it is!

55
00:04:15,791 --> 00:04:18,750
A war such as this would
be absolutely grand!

56
00:04:18,833 --> 00:04:21,000
[scoffs]
This isn't the right time.

57
00:04:21,083 --> 00:04:22,583
We're short on soldiers.

58
00:04:22,666 --> 00:04:25,500
And also, that moron
Teppes is out of commission.

59
00:04:25,583 --> 00:04:28,500
[TORQUE] He let his emotions
get the better of him.

60
00:04:28,583 --> 00:04:30,500
His actions constitute
a betrayal

61
00:04:30,583 --> 00:04:32,500
of the Inquisition's ethic.

62
00:04:32,583 --> 00:04:35,083
Those who cannot control
their feelings

63
00:04:35,166 --> 00:04:38,541
are unworthy to bear
the title of Thaumaturge.

64
00:04:38,625 --> 00:04:39,458
[LISELOTTE gasps]

65
00:04:40,583 --> 00:04:42,041
[ULLMINA sighs]

66
00:04:42,125 --> 00:04:45,208
Konrad and Teppes both proved
to be so troublesome.

67
00:04:45,291 --> 00:04:47,500
Speaking of our more
troublesome colleagues,

68
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:49,666
how do we plan to deal
with Captain Dragunov?

69
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:52,708
Dragunov did as much as he could
to get the chaos

70
00:04:52,791 --> 00:04:54,541
in Rumble Town
under control.

71
00:04:54,625 --> 00:04:56,083
That so?

72
00:04:56,166 --> 00:04:58,000
Then what would you say
about the sorcerers

73
00:04:58,083 --> 00:05:00,083
he allowed
to escape his grasp?

74
00:05:00,166 --> 00:05:01,875
He's not a Thaumaturge.

75
00:05:01,958 --> 00:05:03,833
He may have put
the people's safety first,

76
00:05:03,916 --> 00:05:05,833
but it wasn't
his call to make.

77
00:05:05,916 --> 00:05:07,666
That's true, but...

78
00:05:07,750 --> 00:05:09,916
[TORQUE]
Dragunov's punishment

79
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,083
has already been decided.

80
00:05:15,083 --> 00:05:17,541
[wind whistling]

81
00:05:17,625 --> 00:05:19,833
[stomach rumbles]

82
00:05:19,916 --> 00:05:21,416
[sighs]

83
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:23,083
I get that the people
of Rumble Town

84
00:05:23,166 --> 00:05:25,083
are going through
some difficult times.

85
00:05:25,166 --> 00:05:27,625
But I don't understand
why we have to give them

86
00:05:27,708 --> 00:05:29,333
almost all of our provisions.

87
00:05:29,416 --> 00:05:31,333
We had no other choice.

88
00:05:31,416 --> 00:05:34,875
It will be months before the
town is able to function again.

89
00:05:34,958 --> 00:05:36,833
So if not for the captain's
generosity,

90
00:05:36,916 --> 00:05:38,458
they would be in real trouble.

91
00:05:38,541 --> 00:05:40,833
I know,
but here's the thing, sir.

92
00:05:40,916 --> 00:05:42,875
We haven't had anything
to eat, but jerky

93
00:05:42,958 --> 00:05:45,041
and the occasional
potato, for days.

94
00:05:45,125 --> 00:05:47,333
That's enough complaining.

95
00:05:47,416 --> 00:05:48,750
The captain helped them,

96
00:05:48,833 --> 00:05:51,375
because he felt partly
responsible for Konrad.

97
00:05:54,583 --> 00:05:56,333
[ROOKIE]
In what way?

98
00:05:56,416 --> 00:05:58,833
As a fellow
Inquisition officer?

99
00:05:58,916 --> 00:06:00,541
That's a part of it.

100
00:06:00,625 --> 00:06:01,791
But more importantly,

101
00:06:01,875 --> 00:06:04,125
Konrad served under him
at one point.

102
00:06:04,208 --> 00:06:06,583
Had the captain been able
to change his heart,

103
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:08,250
harm could've been prevented.

104
00:06:08,333 --> 00:06:11,666
Maybe, but there's no way he
could've known what was coming.

105
00:06:11,750 --> 00:06:13,833
And his actions
saved countless lives.

106
00:06:13,916 --> 00:06:15,916
The captain did nothing wrong.

107
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,166
I hope he can see that.

108
00:06:24,166 --> 00:06:27,458
-[trees rustling]
-[birds chirping]

109
00:06:27,541 --> 00:06:30,166
Gather anything that
could possibly be edible.

110
00:06:30,250 --> 00:06:32,458
When in doubt,
keep it out of your mouth!

111
00:06:32,541 --> 00:06:34,500
[SOLDIERS]
Yeah!

112
00:06:34,583 --> 00:06:36,250
I was wondering what
the Captain meant

113
00:06:36,333 --> 00:06:39,041
by "gathering supplies
through conventional means."

114
00:06:39,125 --> 00:06:41,625
He could've just
called it foraging.

115
00:06:41,708 --> 00:06:44,291
Captain, I know
what we can hunt.

116
00:06:44,375 --> 00:06:46,000
There's a creature called
a "mountain rabbit"

117
00:06:46,083 --> 00:06:47,416
native to this region.

118
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:48,791
They're probably small.

119
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:50,041
We'll have to get several.

120
00:06:50,125 --> 00:06:51,708
That should be pretty easy.

121
00:06:51,791 --> 00:06:53,583
Just use that bow of yours,
Captain!

122
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,500
[terrified yelling]

123
00:06:58,583 --> 00:07:01,500
[ROOKIE] How can they call
that monster a rabbit?

124
00:07:01,583 --> 00:07:03,291
[VICE] I don't get it,
either, but I think

125
00:07:03,375 --> 00:07:05,208
the mountain part's
because it's the size of one!

126
00:07:05,291 --> 00:07:06,416
[ROOKIE] Not to split "hares,"

127
00:07:06,500 --> 00:07:07,833
but there's also
a mountain on its back!

128
00:07:10,416 --> 00:07:11,250
[yelps]

129
00:07:11,333 --> 00:07:13,541
[screaming]

130
00:07:14,666 --> 00:07:16,750
[pained grunts]

131
00:07:16,833 --> 00:07:19,416
[panting]
Okay. Looks like we're safe now.

132
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:22,916
I believe that's a little more
rabbit than we bargained for.

133
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,125
Yeah. Maybe we should
hunt something else.

134
00:07:25,208 --> 00:07:26,291
Something small.

135
00:07:26,375 --> 00:07:27,583
[SOLDIERS
murmuring agreement]

136
00:07:27,666 --> 00:07:29,083
Let's see.

137
00:07:29,166 --> 00:07:32,125
The book depicts something known
as a "gigant boar."

138
00:07:32,208 --> 00:07:34,041
Pretty sure that's short
for gigantic!

139
00:07:34,125 --> 00:07:35,625
[SOLDIERS
murmuring agreement]

140
00:07:35,708 --> 00:07:38,125
Well, at any rate, I'm sure
we'll figure something out

141
00:07:38,208 --> 00:07:39,625
before it gets dark.

142
00:07:42,833 --> 00:07:44,583
[PIODON]
So this "Dragunov" guy.

143
00:07:44,666 --> 00:07:46,708
What kind of person is he?

144
00:07:46,791 --> 00:07:48,833
The man's an idealist.

145
00:07:48,916 --> 00:07:50,583
He believes in order
and justice,

146
00:07:50,666 --> 00:07:53,208
and strives to uphold
these ideals where he can.

147
00:07:53,291 --> 00:07:54,875
Yeah?

148
00:07:54,958 --> 00:07:57,625
Sounds like he's a lot
like you, then.

149
00:07:57,708 --> 00:07:59,916
Less so
than you might imagine.

150
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,625
He doesn't lack strength,
but he has little to no faith

151
00:08:02,708 --> 00:08:05,208
in his own ability
to change this world.

152
00:08:05,291 --> 00:08:07,416
That's why
he's still a captain,

153
00:08:07,500 --> 00:08:08,958
while I'm a general.

154
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:12,083
So you do believe you can change
this world on your own.

155
00:08:12,166 --> 00:08:13,750
That's correct.

156
00:08:13,833 --> 00:08:15,791
I wish for a
disciplined world.

157
00:08:15,875 --> 00:08:18,000
One that reflects
my own ethos.

158
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:21,541
And I will bring this world
about through my own strength.

159
00:08:23,958 --> 00:08:27,458
[VICE] We foraged far and wide,
but this is all we could find.

160
00:08:27,541 --> 00:08:30,708
There are times when luck
simply isn't on our side.

161
00:08:30,791 --> 00:08:33,500
This won't be nearly enough
for everyone, sir.

162
00:08:33,583 --> 00:08:35,916
-Do you have a backup plan?
-[DRAGUNOV] Mm.

163
00:08:36,916 --> 00:08:38,333
Only one.

164
00:08:38,416 --> 00:08:40,625
I was hoping
to avoid this, but...

165
00:08:40,708 --> 00:08:43,083
[exhausted groaning]

166
00:08:43,166 --> 00:08:45,583
[typewriting keys clacking]

167
00:08:45,666 --> 00:08:48,833
So, uh,
what did the captain go to do?

168
00:08:48,916 --> 00:08:52,208
My understanding is that he's
contacting some nearby towns.

169
00:08:52,291 --> 00:08:55,166
He'll explain our situation
and request that they help us.

170
00:08:55,250 --> 00:08:56,750
Oh, that sounds great!

171
00:08:56,833 --> 00:08:58,916
We could end up with food
from a city!

172
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,458
But wait, why didn't he just
do that in the first place?

173
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:02,833
-[door opens]
-[ROOKIE] Hmm?

174
00:09:02,916 --> 00:09:04,708
Well, Captain,
did you have any luck with them?

175
00:09:06,916 --> 00:09:09,000
I was worried this might happen.

176
00:09:09,083 --> 00:09:11,666
Our predicament remains
unchanged, gentlemen.

177
00:09:11,750 --> 00:09:13,958
-[SOLDIERS] Huh?
-I contacted several towns,

178
00:09:14,041 --> 00:09:15,875
but none had food to spare.

179
00:09:15,958 --> 00:09:17,833
At least none to spare
for the likes of us.

180
00:09:17,916 --> 00:09:20,000
-[SOLDIER A] None of them?
-[SOLDIER B] But why not?

181
00:09:20,083 --> 00:09:23,583
This is because of Rumble Town.
That right?

182
00:09:23,666 --> 00:09:24,791
Indeed.

183
00:09:24,875 --> 00:09:26,291
I knew that what transpired

184
00:09:26,375 --> 00:09:28,625
would damage the public's trust
in the Inquisition,

185
00:09:28,708 --> 00:09:31,041
but it seems to be even worse
than I thought.

186
00:09:31,125 --> 00:09:32,583
Why, sir?

187
00:09:32,666 --> 00:09:34,791
Captain Konrad was the one
to blame for that.

188
00:09:34,875 --> 00:09:36,875
We all tried to stop him.

189
00:09:36,958 --> 00:09:39,083
We fought to help as many people
as we could!

190
00:09:39,166 --> 00:09:41,750
Details such as that make
no difference.

191
00:09:41,833 --> 00:09:45,083
It only takes a single offender
and the whole lot looks wicked.

192
00:09:45,166 --> 00:09:48,291
Till the uproar around this
subsides, we are all Konrad.

193
00:09:48,375 --> 00:09:50,583
You've gotta be kidding!
That isn't fair at all!

194
00:09:50,666 --> 00:09:52,166
True.

195
00:09:52,250 --> 00:09:54,083
It's far from fair,

196
00:09:54,166 --> 00:09:56,791
and not unlike the way
we treat sorcerers.

197
00:09:56,875 --> 00:09:58,500
Only a few actually hurt anyone

198
00:09:58,583 --> 00:10:00,708
and yet we see them
all as threats.

199
00:10:00,791 --> 00:10:02,000
[gasps]

200
00:10:02,083 --> 00:10:03,708
Hmm.

201
00:10:03,791 --> 00:10:06,458
Well, nothing for it.

202
00:10:06,541 --> 00:10:09,458
I suppose we'll simply
have to find another way.

203
00:10:09,541 --> 00:10:12,208
If we can't find food
and no one helps...

204
00:10:12,291 --> 00:10:13,500
We might all starve.

205
00:10:13,583 --> 00:10:15,875
Keep your backs straight
and your chins up!

206
00:10:15,958 --> 00:10:18,833
Hunger will never defeat us
while we have each other!

207
00:10:18,916 --> 00:10:20,833
[SOLDIERS]
Huh?

208
00:10:20,916 --> 00:10:23,250
[indistinct chattering]

209
00:10:27,458 --> 00:10:29,125
Something wrong?

210
00:10:29,208 --> 00:10:32,125
Oh, uh... I just...

211
00:10:32,208 --> 00:10:34,416
If you're troubled,
make it known.

212
00:10:34,500 --> 00:10:37,875
Well... I suppose
I'm trying to figure out

213
00:10:37,958 --> 00:10:39,875
if there's a point
to what we're doing, sir.

214
00:10:39,958 --> 00:10:42,541
[DRAGUNOV]
How very philosophical.

215
00:10:42,625 --> 00:10:45,083
[ROOKIE] I know that we've been
fighting to help people,

216
00:10:45,166 --> 00:10:47,291
and that's certainly better
than what Konrad did,

217
00:10:47,375 --> 00:10:50,083
but with the way
we're being treated now,

218
00:10:50,166 --> 00:10:53,416
I'm starting to feel as though
no matter how hard we fight,

219
00:10:53,500 --> 00:10:56,125
we'll never actually make
this world any better.

220
00:10:56,208 --> 00:10:57,916
No one even knows we tried.

221
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,208
We don't do the right thing
just to get recognition.

222
00:11:01,291 --> 00:11:02,583
And we certainly don't do it

223
00:11:02,666 --> 00:11:05,041
because it makes life
any easier for us.

224
00:11:05,125 --> 00:11:06,458
But, sir!

225
00:11:06,541 --> 00:11:08,916
Don't you wanna know
you made a difference?

226
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:12,083
[DRAGUNOV] I don't believe that
any single person is capable

227
00:11:12,166 --> 00:11:13,750
of changing this world.

228
00:11:13,833 --> 00:11:15,666
Not on their own.

229
00:11:15,750 --> 00:11:19,125
I'm not that horned sorcerer
who thinks he's going to prove

230
00:11:19,208 --> 00:11:22,291
a fairy tale real
and punch it out of the sky.

231
00:11:22,375 --> 00:11:24,291
-[chuckles]
-Huh?

232
00:11:24,375 --> 00:11:27,625
Look, at the end
of any given day,

233
00:11:27,708 --> 00:11:29,250
the only way I rest easy

234
00:11:29,333 --> 00:11:32,416
is if I strove to do right
by whomever was within my reach.

235
00:11:32,500 --> 00:11:35,208
By whomever's within reach.

236
00:11:35,291 --> 00:11:37,458
[gasps]
Listen, Captain.

237
00:11:38,541 --> 00:11:40,041
About our supplies.

238
00:11:40,125 --> 00:11:43,208
I'm not sure, but I think I know
where we can get more.

239
00:11:43,291 --> 00:11:44,750
Huh?

240
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:47,291
[knocking]

241
00:11:47,375 --> 00:11:50,083
-[VICE] Pardon, sir.
-[door opens]

242
00:11:50,166 --> 00:11:52,208
Were you able to get
in touch with them?

243
00:11:52,291 --> 00:11:53,958
That I was.

244
00:11:54,041 --> 00:11:55,541
I spoke with the townsfolk,

245
00:11:55,625 --> 00:11:57,833
and they've agreed
to supply us with food.

246
00:11:57,916 --> 00:12:01,083
-Really?
-You did it, Captain. Nice work!

247
00:12:01,166 --> 00:12:03,875
Your advice proved to be correct
in this case.

248
00:12:03,958 --> 00:12:05,916
Of course that town
would help us.

249
00:12:07,500 --> 00:12:10,000
Seeing as we risked our lives
protecting them

250
00:12:10,083 --> 00:12:11,541
from the Leviathan Nemesis

251
00:12:11,625 --> 00:12:13,500
that wrecked
Captain Edmund's ship,

252
00:12:13,583 --> 00:12:15,125
they owed us a favor.

253
00:12:16,750 --> 00:12:19,583
That's actually why
I was wary of asking.

254
00:12:19,666 --> 00:12:21,666
I feared that sense of debt
would make them feel

255
00:12:21,750 --> 00:12:24,375
they were obliged,
with no choice.

256
00:12:24,458 --> 00:12:26,250
Sorry, sir.

257
00:12:26,333 --> 00:12:27,500
Don't be.

258
00:12:27,583 --> 00:12:29,583
Believe it or not,
they thanked me.

259
00:12:29,666 --> 00:12:31,625
The people of that town
were grateful

260
00:12:31,708 --> 00:12:34,125
for the chance
to help us in kind.

261
00:12:34,208 --> 00:12:35,416
[BOTH gasp]

262
00:12:35,500 --> 00:12:37,125
[BOTH chuckle]

263
00:12:37,208 --> 00:12:39,458
I guess we were in
their reach this time.

264
00:12:39,541 --> 00:12:40,833
And do you know why that is?

265
00:12:40,916 --> 00:12:42,208
Because of you.

266
00:12:42,291 --> 00:12:44,250
Not only did you risk your life
to save theirs,

267
00:12:44,333 --> 00:12:46,333
you inspired them to be kind.

268
00:12:46,416 --> 00:12:47,958
All of us did.

269
00:12:48,041 --> 00:12:50,208
I think you taught me
something today.

270
00:12:50,291 --> 00:12:52,375
Maybe Rumble Town'll
be the same.

271
00:12:52,458 --> 00:12:54,041
Maybe they'll be kinder, too!

272
00:12:54,125 --> 00:12:55,166
[DRAGUNOV]
Hmm!

273
00:12:55,250 --> 00:12:57,291
[DRAGUNOV]
All right, Vice Captain.

274
00:12:57,375 --> 00:12:59,291
-We'd better change course.
-[BOTH] Huh?

275
00:12:59,375 --> 00:13:00,875
[DRAGUNOV]
Turn the ship around.

276
00:13:00,958 --> 00:13:03,791
Let's head straight to that town
and accept our favor.

277
00:13:03,875 --> 00:13:05,041
[VICE]
Yes, sir!

278
00:13:11,083 --> 00:13:12,958
♪

279
00:13:13,041 --> 00:13:14,708
How are you, Alma?

280
00:13:14,791 --> 00:13:16,458
It's so nice
to finally meet you.

281
00:13:16,541 --> 00:13:17,583
I've heard great things.

282
00:13:17,666 --> 00:13:18,625
[MISTER BOOBRIE
chatters happily]

283
00:13:18,708 --> 00:13:20,250
From what I've been told,

284
00:13:20,333 --> 00:13:22,500
this little screw up
owes you quite a bit.

285
00:13:22,583 --> 00:13:24,541
Uh... Oh, yeah!

286
00:13:24,625 --> 00:13:27,000
Melie's helped me out
since before I even got here!

287
00:13:27,083 --> 00:13:30,250
I mean, I try, but you've
helped me way more.

288
00:13:30,333 --> 00:13:31,333
Seth's great.

289
00:13:31,416 --> 00:13:33,125
He's a very dear friend to me.

290
00:13:33,208 --> 00:13:34,791
[DOC whimpering]

291
00:13:34,875 --> 00:13:37,791
The old crone looks
as mean as ever. Crap!

292
00:13:37,875 --> 00:13:40,208
Huh? Who are you
calling a crone?

293
00:13:40,291 --> 00:13:42,125
You know, Doc helped me
out a lot, too.

294
00:13:42,208 --> 00:13:44,416
That may be, but I only did it
when I had no choice!

295
00:13:44,500 --> 00:13:46,916
And how did you repay me?
By drowning me in debt!

296
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,875
[laughs]
But we had fun, right?

297
00:13:48,958 --> 00:13:50,916
[MELBA]
Sorry for the wait!

298
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:52,666
Here's your coffee. Enjoy!

299
00:13:52,750 --> 00:13:54,166
[DOC]
Ah, thanks a million!

300
00:13:54,250 --> 00:13:55,625
Hmm?

301
00:13:55,708 --> 00:13:57,708
I have to say,
the coffee in Artemis

302
00:13:57,791 --> 00:13:59,666
seems to be a little
on the thin side.

303
00:13:59,750 --> 00:14:01,833
[PAPA] Yes. It's much like
the hair on top of my head.

304
00:14:01,916 --> 00:14:03,291
What's going on?

305
00:14:03,375 --> 00:14:05,458
Is this another one of your
new recipes, Melba?

306
00:14:05,541 --> 00:14:08,291
I'm sorry, guys.
I'll just tell you.

307
00:14:08,375 --> 00:14:09,333
[GROUP]
What?

308
00:14:09,416 --> 00:14:11,416
Kettle Coffee's
out of coffee?

309
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:13,541
[MISTER BOOBRIE
chatters unhappily]

310
00:14:13,625 --> 00:14:16,333
You mean to tell me that this
one little coffee bean

311
00:14:16,416 --> 00:14:18,416
is worth 10,000 dimes?

312
00:14:18,500 --> 00:14:21,208
They're hard to find,
and without these beans...

313
00:14:21,291 --> 00:14:23,708
Kettle Coffee could go
out of business!

314
00:14:23,791 --> 00:14:26,916
I take it this is because
of what happened in Rumble Town?

315
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,208
Why would that make coffee
beans more expensive?

316
00:14:30,291 --> 00:14:31,875
Well, to explain it in terms

317
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:34,583
that your less-than-developed
brain can understand,

318
00:14:34,666 --> 00:14:37,208
Rumble Town's at the crossroads
between the other continents,

319
00:14:37,291 --> 00:14:39,208
so lots of trade routes
run through it.

320
00:14:39,291 --> 00:14:40,416
Uh...

321
00:14:40,500 --> 00:14:42,875
Simply put, nothing grows there,

322
00:14:42,958 --> 00:14:45,625
but traders rely on Rumble Town
as a stopping point

323
00:14:45,708 --> 00:14:47,708
when they're carrying things
like wheat and coffee

324
00:14:47,791 --> 00:14:48,958
to places like Artemis.

325
00:14:49,041 --> 00:14:50,916
Oh! And since Rumble Town

326
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,791
doesn't feel safe
after the riots,

327
00:14:52,875 --> 00:14:55,416
it can't be a halfway point
for commerce right now.

328
00:14:55,500 --> 00:14:57,083
I think I understand!

329
00:14:57,166 --> 00:14:59,250
These traders punked out and
stopped bringin' stuff, right?

330
00:14:59,333 --> 00:15:00,541
[MISTER BOOBRIE vocalizes]

331
00:15:00,625 --> 00:15:02,958
It's a real shame.
I just had a new idea.

332
00:15:03,041 --> 00:15:04,666
I was gonna make
a new coffee blend

333
00:15:04,750 --> 00:15:06,708
with fish as the
secret ingredient.

334
00:15:06,791 --> 00:15:08,500
Yeah, uh... sounds great,

335
00:15:08,583 --> 00:15:10,875
but I'm not sure
if the world's quite ready.

336
00:15:10,958 --> 00:15:14,000
Well, it's too bad,
but at least a lack of coffee

337
00:15:14,083 --> 00:15:15,916
-won't kill anyone.
-[DOC screaming]

338
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,333
Doc? What in the world
is up with you?

339
00:15:18,416 --> 00:15:19,791
How could I forget?

340
00:15:19,875 --> 00:15:21,291
There is actually someone
who might die

341
00:15:21,375 --> 00:15:23,041
if they don't get their coffee!

342
00:15:24,791 --> 00:15:26,416
[DOC yells]

343
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:29,166
Devi! You gotta
hang in there, okay?

344
00:15:29,250 --> 00:15:31,625
[DEVI moaning]

345
00:15:31,708 --> 00:15:33,458
What the heck is that thing?

346
00:15:33,541 --> 00:15:34,916
His name is Devi.

347
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:37,625
He's a Devil Fish Kraken
and he lives down here.

348
00:15:37,708 --> 00:15:39,250
Just look at you, Devi.

349
00:15:39,333 --> 00:15:40,416
You're shriveled up
like a prune!

350
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:41,791
[DEVI moans]

351
00:15:41,875 --> 00:15:44,458
Devi needs some coffee!
We gotta help him out!

352
00:15:44,541 --> 00:15:47,666
My friend! The best friend
I have in this world!

353
00:15:47,750 --> 00:15:50,208
Well said. We won't
leave Devi out to dry.

354
00:15:50,291 --> 00:15:52,000
Seth and I have your back, Doc!

355
00:15:52,083 --> 00:15:53,583
Right? Don't we?

356
00:15:53,666 --> 00:15:56,333
He looks kind of
tasty right now.

357
00:15:56,416 --> 00:15:58,958
[DOC] What's wrong with you?
How could you say that?

358
00:15:59,041 --> 00:16:01,666
Not cool, Seth.
Friends don't eat each other!

359
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:03,416
We just need coffee, right?

360
00:16:03,500 --> 00:16:05,250
It can't be all
that hard to find.

361
00:16:05,333 --> 00:16:08,125
Just leave it to us!

362
00:16:08,208 --> 00:16:09,500
[MELBA giggles]

363
00:16:09,583 --> 00:16:11,708
They're such good friends.
I'm kinda jealous.

364
00:16:11,791 --> 00:16:15,375
Yeah. I'm startin' to remember
why I left here.

365
00:16:15,458 --> 00:16:18,041
Don't you worry, Devi.
You're gonna get through this.

366
00:16:18,125 --> 00:16:19,833
What are they doing?

367
00:16:19,916 --> 00:16:22,000
And why is it taking 'em
so long?

368
00:16:22,083 --> 00:16:24,333
-[SETH] We're back!
-[DOC exclaiming]

369
00:16:24,416 --> 00:16:27,041
[SETH giggles]
Here's your coffee!

370
00:16:27,125 --> 00:16:30,000
[DOC] Oh, wow!
You actually found some!

371
00:16:30,083 --> 00:16:32,166
I never doubted you
for one second!

372
00:16:32,250 --> 00:16:33,916
This deep black liquid.

373
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:36,791
It's the real deal, no doubt!

374
00:16:36,875 --> 00:16:39,166
-[spewing]
-This is squid ink, you dolt!

375
00:16:39,250 --> 00:16:40,625
So it's bad.

376
00:16:40,708 --> 00:16:42,333
[DOC]
Coffee comes from beans!

377
00:16:42,416 --> 00:16:43,583
Go get me some beans!

378
00:16:43,666 --> 00:16:44,625
[MELIE slurping]

379
00:16:44,708 --> 00:16:46,083
[MELIE]
This is tasty, though.

380
00:16:47,291 --> 00:16:48,791
[SETH]
We got it this time!

381
00:16:50,208 --> 00:16:51,875
Much better. Thanks so much.

382
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:54,125
[groans]

383
00:16:54,208 --> 00:16:56,041
Wrong again!
These are fava beans!

384
00:16:56,125 --> 00:16:57,166
Look at 'em!

385
00:16:57,250 --> 00:16:59,416
Well, yeah.
You asked for beans.

386
00:16:59,500 --> 00:17:01,458
[DOC] Different plant!
These beans are for eating!

387
00:17:01,541 --> 00:17:04,041
[MELIE]
Mm! I'll say they are.

388
00:17:06,458 --> 00:17:08,708
[SETH] 'Kay!
How about this?

389
00:17:08,791 --> 00:17:10,416
Wow, this is perfect.

390
00:17:10,500 --> 00:17:12,250
[DOC] Wrong!
Do you have any idea

391
00:17:12,333 --> 00:17:14,958
how long that thing'll take
to start makin' beans?

392
00:17:15,041 --> 00:17:17,458
Hurry up and grow big,
okay, buddy?

393
00:17:19,458 --> 00:17:21,666
[SETH] Don't forget,
we need coffee beans!

394
00:17:21,750 --> 00:17:22,916
Coffee beans!

395
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,500
[MELIE]
Coffee beans! Coffee beans!

396
00:17:24,583 --> 00:17:27,291
-[SETH] Coffee beans!
-[MELIE] Coffee beans!

397
00:17:28,291 --> 00:17:29,625
Oh, boy.

398
00:17:29,708 --> 00:17:32,166
What does that idiot
think he's doing now?

399
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:34,083
[DEVI groaning]

400
00:17:34,166 --> 00:17:35,833
Don't give up on me, 'kay?

401
00:17:35,916 --> 00:17:37,958
'Cause I'm never gonna
give up on you!

402
00:17:39,250 --> 00:17:41,458
I don't know how far
they went searching,

403
00:17:41,541 --> 00:17:43,791
but it looks like they
just couldn't swing it.

404
00:17:43,875 --> 00:17:45,625
[SETH panting]

405
00:17:45,708 --> 00:17:47,083
You're back.

406
00:17:48,125 --> 00:17:51,083
Hey, Doc. I got it.
For real.

407
00:17:51,166 --> 00:17:52,625
Oh, yeah?

408
00:17:52,708 --> 00:17:54,041
Are you sure you didn't
get it mixed up

409
00:17:54,125 --> 00:17:55,791
with bat poo or somethin'?

410
00:17:55,875 --> 00:17:57,208
[gasps]

411
00:17:57,291 --> 00:17:58,833
Whoa, these coffee beans

412
00:17:58,916 --> 00:18:00,500
are the real deal.
I can smell 'em!

413
00:18:00,583 --> 00:18:02,375
Where in the world
did you pick this up from?

414
00:18:02,458 --> 00:18:05,041
Nowhere.
So we need to be fast, right?

415
00:18:05,125 --> 00:18:07,208
Let's hurry up and
have Devi drink some.

416
00:18:07,291 --> 00:18:08,666
[DOC gasps]

417
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:11,208
[DOC] I take back everything
I've said about you!

418
00:18:13,166 --> 00:18:14,750
[DOC]
Careful, it's hot.

419
00:18:14,833 --> 00:18:16,500
Take your time, okay?

420
00:18:16,583 --> 00:18:18,000
[glugging]

421
00:18:18,083 --> 00:18:19,708
Feel any better?

422
00:18:19,791 --> 00:18:21,291
[DEVI moans]

423
00:18:21,375 --> 00:18:24,875
[roaring]

424
00:18:24,958 --> 00:18:28,208
-All right, we saved Devi!
-I'm so glad he's okay!

425
00:18:28,291 --> 00:18:29,333
[MISTER BOOBRIE
chatters happily]

426
00:18:29,416 --> 00:18:31,166
-[DEVI roars]
-Huh.

427
00:18:31,250 --> 00:18:34,041
Fresh off the brink of death,
and you're sharin' already.

428
00:18:34,125 --> 00:18:35,083
[DOC chuckles]

429
00:18:35,166 --> 00:18:36,916
[MELBA]
Huh? Hey.

430
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,875
Seth, what's that
in your back pocket?

431
00:18:39,958 --> 00:18:43,375
Oh, this? It's the bill for
the coffee beans.

432
00:18:43,458 --> 00:18:44,875
They were really expensive,

433
00:18:44,958 --> 00:18:47,375
but Majesty said I could
pay him back later.

434
00:18:47,458 --> 00:18:50,000
Hmm? So this was from him?

435
00:18:50,083 --> 00:18:52,125
[MELBA]
How much did they cost?

436
00:18:52,208 --> 00:18:55,166
Hold on. Let me figure out
all these zeros.

437
00:18:56,250 --> 00:18:57,500
A hundred million dimes.

438
00:18:57,583 --> 00:18:58,958
[DOC screams]

439
00:18:59,041 --> 00:19:01,000
-Huh? Doc?
-[MELBA] Oh, dear!

440
00:19:01,083 --> 00:19:02,500
This is just terrible!

441
00:19:02,583 --> 00:19:05,500
We saved Devi, but now Doc's
on death's door!

442
00:19:05,583 --> 00:19:07,416
I'll be damned.

443
00:19:07,500 --> 00:19:10,166
A cup of joe worth
a hundred million dimes.

444
00:19:10,250 --> 00:19:12,000
Lovely.

445
00:19:12,083 --> 00:19:14,041
I'm coming home!

446
00:19:14,125 --> 00:19:16,666
[GROUP]
Doc!

447
00:19:17,791 --> 00:19:19,500
[DOC]
Don't mourn my death!

448
00:19:19,583 --> 00:19:21,916
Celebrate my life.

449
00:19:26,416 --> 00:19:27,958
-[SOLDIERS chattering]
-[silverware clinking]

450
00:19:28,041 --> 00:19:30,583
[SOLDIER A] We haven't had the
captain's cooking in ages!

451
00:19:30,666 --> 00:19:33,583
-Man, it's good!
-[SOLDIER B] You said it!

452
00:19:33,666 --> 00:19:36,125
This is exactly what
the doctor ordered.

453
00:19:36,208 --> 00:19:37,833
[ROOKIE chuckling]

454
00:19:37,916 --> 00:19:40,666
Hey, speaking of the captain,
do you know where he is?

455
00:19:42,208 --> 00:19:44,000
-[VICE] Captain.
-[DRAGUNOV] Huh?

456
00:19:44,083 --> 00:19:47,000
[VICE] I take it that's a
summons from headquarters?

457
00:19:47,083 --> 00:19:49,125
[laughs]
Indeed it is.

458
00:19:49,208 --> 00:19:51,208
From General Torque himself,
actually.

459
00:19:51,291 --> 00:19:52,583
[VICE]
What?

460
00:19:52,666 --> 00:19:53,916
My apologies,

461
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:56,041
but I'll be leaving the ship
in your charge.

462
00:19:56,125 --> 00:19:58,666
And when the men talk about
Rumble Town,

463
00:19:58,750 --> 00:20:00,500
I forced them to obey me.

464
00:20:00,583 --> 00:20:02,416
They had no choice, all right?

465
00:20:02,500 --> 00:20:05,666
They can't actually plan
to reprimand you.

466
00:20:05,750 --> 00:20:08,500
They may, but there's
no need to worry.

467
00:20:08,583 --> 00:20:10,041
Even if they throw
the book at me,

468
00:20:10,125 --> 00:20:11,916
I ought to be back in time.

469
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:15,333
The only reservation I had
was about our soldiers.

470
00:20:15,416 --> 00:20:16,916
Arrogant as this thinking is,

471
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,416
I wasn't certain they'd be
all right without me.

472
00:20:19,500 --> 00:20:21,125
[ROOKIE gasps]

473
00:20:21,208 --> 00:20:24,833
But now, I can see that
my fears were unfounded.

474
00:20:24,916 --> 00:20:26,458
The men have proven
they can take care

475
00:20:26,541 --> 00:20:28,166
of themselves beyond a doubt.

476
00:20:28,250 --> 00:20:31,125
That they can, sir.

477
00:20:31,208 --> 00:20:33,125
[DRAGUNOV]
Best of luck to you.

478
00:20:33,208 --> 00:20:36,083
Remember to protect those
who fall within your reach.

479
00:20:36,166 --> 00:20:38,541
Take care of yourself, sir.

480
00:20:38,625 --> 00:20:41,375
We'll make certain the ship
is ready for your return.

481
00:20:41,458 --> 00:20:43,708
It's your ship.
And we are your men.

482
00:20:43,791 --> 00:20:45,708
[DRAGUNOV]
Don't be so formal.

483
00:20:45,791 --> 00:20:48,125
And remember to take breaks!

484
00:20:48,208 --> 00:20:49,833
[ROOKIE crying]

485
00:20:51,416 --> 00:20:52,500
[DRAGUNOV]
There are times

486
00:20:52,583 --> 00:20:55,125
when if you wish
to protect a place,

487
00:20:55,208 --> 00:20:57,458
you have no choice
but to leave it.

488
00:20:57,541 --> 00:20:59,083
I wonder...

489
00:20:59,166 --> 00:21:02,000
where's that horned boy now?

490
00:21:04,625 --> 00:21:07,083
Today turned out to be
surprisingly exciting,

491
00:21:07,166 --> 00:21:08,916
wouldn't you agree?

492
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:10,833
[SETH]
Yeah. It did.

493
00:21:12,166 --> 00:21:13,166
You okay?

494
00:21:13,250 --> 00:21:14,583
Uh, yeah, I'm good.

495
00:21:14,666 --> 00:21:16,666
I think I'm gonna shove off
and call it a day.

496
00:21:16,750 --> 00:21:19,041
Sure.
Have a good night, okay?

497
00:21:19,125 --> 00:21:21,208
I'll see you tomorrow.

498
00:21:21,291 --> 00:21:23,000
[MISTER BOOBRIE
vocalizes happily]

499
00:21:23,083 --> 00:21:24,666
[SETH chuckles]

500
00:21:24,750 --> 00:21:25,625
[door closes]

501
00:21:26,583 --> 00:21:28,125
[sighs]

502
00:21:28,208 --> 00:21:30,375
♪

503
00:21:35,125 --> 00:21:36,125
[gasps]

504
00:21:37,250 --> 00:21:39,416
[ALMA] Look. It's not like
running in place

505
00:21:39,500 --> 00:21:42,041
and getting nowhere
is new for you.

506
00:21:42,125 --> 00:21:45,708
But today was especially bad,
even for you.

507
00:21:45,791 --> 00:21:47,916
I was just...

508
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,625
I know why you feel like you
have to keep charging forward.

509
00:21:51,708 --> 00:21:54,916
It's 'cause your regrets catch
up with you when you slow down.

510
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,708
Or am I mistaken?

511
00:21:56,791 --> 00:21:57,916
[gasps]

512
00:21:58,000 --> 00:21:59,500
That's true.

513
00:21:59,583 --> 00:22:01,833
I was surprised to see this,

514
00:22:01,916 --> 00:22:03,208
but you truly
do seem to be

515
00:22:03,291 --> 00:22:06,250
at home here
at the Artemis Institute.

516
00:22:06,333 --> 00:22:09,583
After Rumble Town, though,
you're starting to have doubts.

517
00:22:09,666 --> 00:22:11,791
I see that you're scared
of something.

518
00:22:11,875 --> 00:22:14,291
Just can't say what.

519
00:22:14,375 --> 00:22:15,625
[SETH sighs]

520
00:22:15,708 --> 00:22:19,375
I'm scared that I'm
the monster after all.

521
00:22:19,458 --> 00:22:21,375
[ALMA]
Hmm.

522
00:22:21,458 --> 00:22:22,500
[SETH inhales sharply]

523
00:22:22,583 --> 00:22:23,875
So, am I?

524
00:22:23,958 --> 00:22:26,958
♪

525
00:24:07,750 --> 00:24:10,416
[NARRATOR] Seth resolves
to depart on a new journey,

526
00:24:10,500 --> 00:24:12,791
and seek out
the secrets of Radiant.

527
00:24:12,875 --> 00:24:14,250
But on the day he's to leave,

528
00:24:14,333 --> 00:24:17,083
a mighty Nemesis lands
in the Artemis Institute.

529
00:24:17,166 --> 00:24:18,958
Seth fights to protect Melie,

530
00:24:19,041 --> 00:24:22,166
and when pushed too far,
he loses control once again.

531
00:24:22,250 --> 00:24:24,375
What is the nature
of his latent power?

532
00:24:24,458 --> 00:24:27,291
And what lies ahead
on the voyage to come?

533
00:24:27,375 --> 00:24:28,666
Next time on Radiant:

534
00:24:28,750 --> 00:24:31,291
"In Search of the Future."

